s of length, and she gives the example of "a short%0a%3c break", while other languages speak in terms of volume (e.g. Spanish) with an example of "a small break". In a similar fashion, Boroditsky gives examples where time can be organized from left to right or vice versa (typically depending on how the language is written) or based on the orientation of the land. In other words, English speakers generally organize a timeline left-to-right, while the Kuuk Thaayorre people organized time east-to-west no matter which direction they were facing.%0a%3c %0a%3c On their own, these differences don't seem particularly insightful or enlightening, but when you put different people on different tasks, it's likely to be done and perceived much differently based on what language they speak. I think many of us often forget that language plays a very large role in the way we see, understand, and explain the world, and it's entirely possible that sometimes there's a better-suited way.%0a%3c %0a%3c All of this is a bit inspiring to me. I'm always a fan of playing Devil's advocate and trying to see from all perspectives, and this seems like one of the ultimate ways to do that: literally change the way I think by speaking another language. It's a little silly to be the major motivation behind learning a language, but I do think it's a valuable piece of knowledge, and helps enforce the idea that diversity in not just thought but all things is likely to yield better results than uniformity would.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c %0a%3c -https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RKK7wGAYP6k%0a%3c %0a%3c -https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2sw-oRR2D8&t=39s%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
